127
00:11:03.496 --> 00:11:05.373  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-They are.
-But, um...

128
00:11:05.456 --> 00:11:07.083  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
I know they're identical animals...

129
00:11:07.166 --> 00:11:08.834  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-Yeah.
-...but are they the same?

130
00:11:08.918 --> 00:11:10.294  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-They are.
-So, they...

131
00:11:10.961 --> 00:11:12.755  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-They are one animal. I--
-Yep.

132
00:11:12.838 --> 00:11:13.964  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
It's one animal.

133
00:11:14.048 --> 00:11:16.092  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Okay, but they're not considered...

134
00:11:17.093 --> 00:11:18.803  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
I thought polyp was an animal...

135
00:11:20.304 --> 00:11:23.766  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
not a coral was an animal
with lots of polyps.

136
00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:26.852  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-That make sense?
-A coral is an animal with lots of polyps.

137
00:11:27.812 --> 00:11:29.355  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
But the polyp isn't an animal?

138
00:11:30.648 --> 00:11:32.817  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Well... it's part of the animal.

139
00:11:33.192 --> 00:11:35.820  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Right. 'Cause this is a--
No one's ever explained...

140
00:11:36.237 --> 00:11:38.030  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-what a coral is.
-Your amazement is,

141
00:11:38.114 --> 00:11:39.448  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
why did you not know that?

142
00:11:39.532 --> 00:11:41.450  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-Why didn't I know that?
-I'm stunned.

143
00:11:41.534 --> 00:11:43.369  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
-And it's the--
-You're a smart guy.

144
00:11:43.744 --> 00:11:45.663  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
What's wrong with you? [laughing]

145
00:11:48.916 --> 00:11:53.129  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
I get completely overwhelmed sometimes,
underwater, on a reef.

146
00:11:53.379 --> 00:11:56.632  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
Because I can't believe
that these structures

147
00:11:56.715 --> 00:11:58.801  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
are sort of created
by these simple organisms,

148
00:11:58.884 --> 00:12:00.386  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
or "seemingly" simple organisms.

149
00:12:00.469 --> 00:12:04.265  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
I have the utmost respect for corals,
'cause I think they've got us all fooled.

150
00:12:04.348 --> 00:12:07.518  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Simplicity on the outside
doesn't mean simplicity on the inside.

151
00:12:07.893 --> 00:12:11.063  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
We think we're really evolved
'cause we're highly complex beings.

152
00:12:11.147 --> 00:12:13.441  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
We can do lots of things.
We have opposing thumbs.

153
00:12:14.108 --> 00:12:18.070  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
But corals... they've decided,
"Forget the external complexity.

154
00:12:18.154 --> 00:12:21.991  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Let's just be really sophisticated
in a quiet way."

155
00:12:23.325 --> 00:12:26.078  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>A coral individual is really made up</i>

156
00:12:26.162 --> 00:12:30.791  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>of thousands of small structures</i>
<i>called polyps.</i>

157
00:12:32.126 --> 00:12:35.921  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
<i>Each polyp is a circular mouth...</i>

158
00:12:36.505 --> 00:12:38.799  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>surrounded by tentacles...</i>

159
00:12:39.550 --> 00:12:43.053  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>and they can combine</i>
<i>to be millions of them</i>

160
00:12:43.137 --> 00:12:44.597  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>across a single animal.</i>

161
00:12:45.764 --> 00:12:49.894  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>They have, inside their tissues,</i>
<i>small plants,</i>

162
00:12:49.977 --> 00:12:51.353  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>these microalgae...</i>

163
00:12:51.812 --> 00:12:53.689  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>a million per centimeter squared.</i>

164
00:12:54.690 --> 00:12:58.194  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>The plants that live inside them</i>
<i>photosynthesize,</i>

165
00:12:58.277 --> 00:13:00.488  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>and the animal uses that for their food.</i>

166
00:13:01.113 --> 00:13:04.492  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>They essentially have food factories</i>
<i>living inside of themselves.</i>

167
00:13:05.367 --> 00:13:07.077  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>So, as the animal grows,</i>

168
00:13:07.161 --> 00:13:11.916  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>what you see is the animal is growing</i>
<i>over the skeleton</i>

169
00:13:11.999 --> 00:13:14.001  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>and depositing the skeleton underneath it.</i>

170
00:13:22.468 --> 00:13:24.595  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>They photosynthesize during the day.</i>

171
00:13:25.012 --> 00:13:26.055  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>At night...</i>

172
00:13:26.430 --> 00:13:29.808  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>the plant's really essentially asleep</i>
<i>and the animal comes active.</i>

173
00:13:29.892 --> 00:13:32.144  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>They expand their polyps.</i>

174
00:13:32.228 --> 00:13:33.854  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>The tentacles come out.</i>

175
00:13:33.938 --> 00:13:37.525  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>And now anything</i>
<i>that swims by is caught</i>

176
00:13:37.608 --> 00:13:40.986  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>by these stinging cells</i>
<i>that are on the tips of the tentacles.</i>

177
00:13:42.947 --> 00:13:46.158  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>There are many different species</i>
<i>of corals,</i>

178
00:13:46.242 --> 00:13:50.454  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>and the different species of corals</i>
<i>are different shapes.</i>

179
00:13:50.538 --> 00:13:54.166  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Some are very boring to look at.</i>
<i>They look like big rocks on the bottom.</i>

180
00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:56.168  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>Some are incredibly beautiful to look at.</i>

181
00:13:56.252 --> 00:14:00.798  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>They have huge, huge branching patterns,</i>
<i>or massive plates.</i>

182
00:14:01.757 --> 00:14:04.260  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>Some of them look like petals of a flower.</i>

183
00:14:06.637 --> 00:14:09.139  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>These are foundation species.</i>

184
00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:12.226  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>They have all these other organisms</i>
<i>that depend on them.</i>

185
00:14:12.768 --> 00:14:15.062  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>They are the reason we have reefs.</i>

186
00:14:16.105 --> 00:14:19.984  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>A consortium of organisms</i>
<i>that cooperate together...</i>

187
00:14:21.694 --> 00:14:24.530  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>that now manifests</i>
<i>in this massive structure</i>

188
00:14:24.613 --> 00:14:26.407  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>that can be seen from space.</i>

189
00:14:38.836 --> 00:14:42.923  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Vevers] <i>There's a famous reef</i>
<i>in American Samoa called Airport Reef.</i>

190
00:14:43.465 --> 00:14:48.053  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>We heard that there was an area</i>
<i>where the corals were turning white.</i>

191
00:14:49.388 --> 00:14:52.391  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Because we'd been there previously</i>
<i>to do a survey...</i>

192
00:14:52.850 --> 00:14:55.728  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>we wanted to go back</i>
<i>and take the same images again.</i>

193
00:15:09.199 --> 00:15:11.660  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>I was truly shocked by what I saw.</i>

194
00:15:12.995 --> 00:15:15.706  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>The reef was white</i>
<i>as far as the eye could see.</i>

195
00:15:18.042 --> 00:15:21.712  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>To be honest, I didn't have the knowledge</i>
<i>to know how to process it.</i>

196
00:15:22.796 --> 00:15:23.839  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>Was this dead?</i>

197
00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:25.382  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>Was it alive?</i>

198
00:15:33.265 --> 00:15:35.392  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>This is... Airport Reef.</i>

199
00:15:37.561 --> 00:15:39.104  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Before. So, this is in December.

200
00:15:43.067 --> 00:15:44.193  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>And that's it now.</i>

201
00:15:54.203 --> 00:15:56.330  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Hoegh-Guldberg]
<i>When Richard saw that white coral,</i>

202
00:15:56.413 --> 00:15:57.790  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>it was a turning point for him.</i>

203
00:15:59.792 --> 00:16:03.087  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
I think I admitted to him
that I thought this was far more deadly

204
00:16:03.170 --> 00:16:05.464  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
than some of the other things
that are facing reefs.

205
00:16:05.923 --> 00:16:08.842  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
And so, what we've seen
since the early 1980s

206
00:16:08.926 --> 00:16:10.177  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
when this first occurs,

207
00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:12.972  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
we've actually lost an enormous amount
of coral,

208
00:16:13.055 --> 00:16:14.640  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
just due to this phenomenon alone.

209
00:16:14.723 --> 00:16:18.268  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>I think that was the first time</i>
<i>that he saw the enormity of the issue.</i>

210
00:16:19.019 --> 00:16:22.898  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
That this was a threat across the planet
to coral reefs,

211
00:16:22.982 --> 00:16:27.111  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
which would happen very quickly
and cause a lot of damage.

212
00:16:29.279 --> 00:16:32.449  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Back in the '80s, we started looking</i>
<i>at this weird phenomenon.</i>

213
00:16:34.284 --> 00:16:37.121  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Large sections of--</i>
<i>of reefs were turning white,</i>

214
00:16:37.204 --> 00:16:38.747  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>literally over a couple of weeks.</i>

215
00:16:39.373 --> 00:16:41.417  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>And no one really knew why this was.</i>

216
00:16:44.294 --> 00:16:46.547  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>As we did more and more experiments,</i>

217
00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:49.049  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>it turned out that it wasn't a disease,</i>

218
00:16:49.133 --> 00:16:50.759  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>it wasn't too much light.</i>

219
00:16:50.843 --> 00:16:53.220  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>And the only thing you could do</i>
<i>in an experiment</i>

220
00:16:53.303 --> 00:16:55.431  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
<i>that would cause corals to go white</i>

221
00:16:55.514 --> 00:16:58.892  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
<i>was to raise the temperature</i>
<i>by two degrees Celsius.</i>

222
00:17:01.311 --> 00:17:03.731  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
<i>By the end of my PhD,</i>

223
00:17:03.814 --> 00:17:07.067  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
<i>we were putting cautious words</i>
<i>in the literature saying:</i>

224
00:17:07.151 --> 00:17:09.862  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>"Well, you know,</i>
<i>maybe this is global warming,</i>

225
00:17:09.945 --> 00:17:12.322  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>and this is one of the early impacts</i>
<i>on reefs."</i>

226
00:17:19.621 --> 00:17:23.417  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Vevers] <i>We look at climate change</i>
<i>as if it's an issue in the air.</i>

227
00:17:23.500 --> 00:17:26.003  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>And you go, "One or two degrees Celsius?</i>

228
00:17:26.253 --> 00:17:27.421  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>Does that really matter?"</i>

229
00:17:28.589 --> 00:17:30.340  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>But when you talk about the ocean...</i>

230
00:17:30.883 --> 00:17:33.093  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>it's like your body temperature changing.</i>

231
00:17:33.761 --> 00:17:38.348  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
And imagine your body temperature
rises one degree centigrade

232
00:17:38.432 --> 00:17:39.933  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
or two degrees centigrade.

233
00:17:40.476 --> 00:17:42.561  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
Over a period of time,
that would be fatal.

234
00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:47.399  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
And that's the seriousness of the issue
when you look at it in terms of the ocean.

235
00:17:50.110 --> 00:17:54.198  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Gates] <i>Coral bleaching itself</i>
<i>is a stress response,</i>

236
00:17:54.281 --> 00:17:58.827  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>much like a fever in humans</i>
<i>is a stress response.</i>

237
00:18:00.037 --> 00:18:03.332  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>If the temperature spikes just</i>
<i>a little bit above their normal range...</i>

238
00:18:04.041 --> 00:18:06.126  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>corals will start to bleach.</i>

239
00:18:07.002 --> 00:18:09.171  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>The small plants</i>
<i>that live inside their tissues,</i>

240
00:18:09.254 --> 00:18:15.469  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>their ability to photosynthesize</i>
<i>and feed the animal host is impaired.</i>

241
00:18:16.011 --> 00:18:18.847  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>The animal essentially senses that:</i>

242
00:18:18.931 --> 00:18:22.434  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
"I've got something inside of me
that is not doing what I expect it to do,"

243
00:18:22.518 --> 00:18:24.728  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
and as happens with us, with--

244
00:18:24.812 --> 00:18:26.605  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
When we get a bacteria,

245
00:18:26.688 --> 00:18:28.524  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
we try to get rid of it
as quickly as possible.

246
00:18:28.607 --> 00:18:30.859  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>That's exactly what these animals do.</i>

247
00:18:30.943 --> 00:18:33.987  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>They try to get rid of those plants</i>
<i>that are no longer functional...</i>

248
00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:38.283  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>and leave behind the transparent,</i>
<i>naked tissue.</i>

249
00:18:39.284 --> 00:18:43.080  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>They've lost the very most important</i>
<i>food source that they have.</i>

250
00:18:43.163 --> 00:18:44.456  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>So, it's starting to starve.</i>

251
00:18:48.460 --> 00:18:50.671  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[Vevers] <i>When the coral bleaches,</i>

252
00:18:50.754 --> 00:18:52.631  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>the flesh becomes clear.</i>

253
00:18:52.714 --> 00:18:55.509  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>And what you're seeing</i>
<i>is its skeleton underneath.</i>

254
